What is a Future?
    Introduced in Java 5, a Future acts as a placeholder for a result that will eventually appear.

The Problem with Future
    The main issue with a standard Future is that it is blocking and passive. 
    To get the result, you must call .get(), which stops the current thread until the task completes. 
    You cannot say, "When this task finishes, do this next task," without manually waiting.

What is a CompletableFuture?
    Introduced in Java 8, CompletableFuture implements both the Future and CompletionStage interfaces.
    It is active and non-blocking. 
    It allows you to orchestrate complex asynchronous workflows using a functional programming style.

Feature                  Future                                                    CompletableFuture
Manual Completion        Cannot be completed manually.                             Can be manually completed using .complete(value).
                         You just wait for the task to finish.
Chaining                 No way to chain tasks together.                           "Supports chaining using .thenApply(), .thenAccept(), etc."
Non-blocking             Requires .get() (blocking) to retrieve the result.         Provides callbacks that execute automatically when the result is ready.
Exception Handling       No built-in way to handle exceptions within the pipeline.  Has dedicated methods like .exceptionally() or .handle().
Combining                You cannot easily combine multiple Future objects.         Can combine multiple stages using thenCombine() or allOf().

Why We Prefer CompletableFuture
A. Functional Chaining (The "Pipeline" approach)
    With CompletableFuture, you can define a sequence of actions that happen one after another without blocking the main thread:
        CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> "Fetching Data...")
            .thenApply(data -> data + " - Processing")
            .thenAccept(finalResult -> System.out.println(finalResult));
B. Non-Blocking Orchestration
    You can trigger multiple independent tasks and act only when all of them or any of them are finished:
        allOf(): Wait for a group of independent tasks to complete.
        anyOf(): Useful when you have redundant sources and only need the fastest result.

C. Exception Handling
    In a standard Future, if something goes wrong, the exception is only thrown when you call .get(). 
    In CompletableFuture, you can catch and recover from errors gracefully:
        .exceptionally(ex -> {
            System.out.println("Error occurred: " + ex.getMessage());
            return "Default Value"; // Recover with a fallback
        })
D. Asynchronous Workflows
      It integrates perfectly with the ForkJoinPool, allowing you to perform heavy I/O or CPU-bound tasks in the background, 
      keeping your main application responsive—which is essential for modern high-performance services.

When to use which?:
    Use Future only if you are working with legacy code or have a very simple "fire and forget" task where you only need to check isDone() occasionally.
    Use CompletableFuture for everything else. It is the modern standard for writing clean, readable, and efficient asynchronous code in Java.

CompletableFuture in multiple consumer calls:
    Yes, CompletableFuture is one of the most efficient ways to handle multiple external API calls in a Java environment. 
    It is specifically designed to solve the "Aggregation" problem—where you need to fetch data from different sources and merge them into a single response.
    When dealing with external APIs, you are often waiting on I/O (network latency). 
    Instead of waiting for API A to finish before calling API B, you can fire them all at once.

How to Orchestrate Multiple API Calls:
  Depending on how your APIs depend on each other, you’ll use different patterns:

1. Parallel Execution (Independent APIs)
    If you need to call API A and API B at the same time and combine their results, use thenCombine. 
    This reduces your total response time to the duration of the slowest call, rather than the sum of both.
        CompletableFuture<User> userFuture = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> api.getUser(id));
        CompletableFuture<Order> orderFuture = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> api.getOrders(id));
        
        // Combine them when both are done
        UserOrders result = userFuture.thenCombine(orderFuture, (user, orders) -> {
            return new UserOrders(user, orders);
        }).join(); // Wait for the final merged result
2. Dependent Execution (Chaining)
    If you need the output of API A to call API B, use thenCompose. 
    This is similar to flatMap in streams; it flattens the nested futures so you don't end up with CompletableFuture<CompletableFuture<T>>.
      CompletableFuture<List<Order>> orders = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> api.getUser(id))
          .thenCompose(user -> api.getOrdersForUser(user.getAccountId()));
3. The "Fan-In" Pattern (Many APIs)
    If you are calling a variable number of APIs (e.g., fetching details for 10 different products), use CompletableFuture.allOf().
    How it works: You create a list of futures. allOf creates a new future that completes only when every single one in the list is done.
    Processing: After allOf().join(), you can map over your original list to collect the results into your final DTO.

Why This is Preferred for Microservices:
Thread Efficiency: 
      While waiting for the external API to respond, the thread is not sitting idle; 
      it's returned to the pool to handle other incoming requests.
Resilience (Timeouts): 
      You can easily attach timeouts to your external calls. 
      If API B is hanging, you can ensure it doesn't bring down your entire service:
    future.orTimeout(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS)
          .exceptionally(ex -> fallbackData);
Clean Aggregation: 
    It avoids "Callback Hell." You can keep your aggregation logic in a single service layer,
    making the code much easier to read and maintain compared to manual thread management.

What is ForkJoinPool?
  Introduced in Java 7, the ForkJoinPool is a specialized implementation of the ExecutorService designed to handle recursive tasks.
  It is built on a simple yet powerful concept: break a large, complex task into smaller sub-tasks until they are simple enough to be solved sequentially.

The framework uses two main operations:
    Fork: Recursively splitting a task into smaller independent sub-tasks.
    Join: Waiting for the sub-tasks to finish and merging their results back together.

2. The Secret Sauce: Work-Stealing Algorithm
      What makes ForkJoinPool different from a standard ThreadPoolExecutor is the Work-Stealing Algorithm.
      In a traditional thread pool, if one thread finishes its queue, it sits idle. 
      In a ForkJoinPool, every thread has its own double-ended queue (deque). 
      If a thread finishes its own work, it "steals" tasks from the back of another busy thread's queue.

Why this matters:
    This ensures maximum CPU utilization. 
    It prevents "starvation" where some threads are overworked while others are doing nothing, making it incredibly efficient for multi-core processors.

3. Where is it used?
Java Parallel Streams: When you call .parallelStream(), Java uses the Common ForkJoinPool under the hood to split the stream and process elements in parallel.
CompletableFuture: By default, if you don't provide a custom executor to supplyAsync, it runs your task in the Common ForkJoinPool.
Recursive Algorithms: It is the go-to choice for tasks like sorting large datasets (QuickSort/MergeSort), searching complex tree structures, or image processing.

4. Why We Prefer It
  A. Efficiency with Recursive Work
      Standard thread pools struggle with tasks that create more tasks. 
      If a thread in a regular pool waits for a sub-task, it stays blocked.
      In ForkJoinPool, the thread can simply pick up another sub-task while waiting, avoiding deadlocks and idle time.
  B. Optimized for Multi-core CPUs
      It is designed to scale with the hardware. 
      As modern servers move toward 16, 32, or 64-core architectures, ForkJoinPool ensures that all those cores are actually doing work rather than managing thread overhead.
  C. Low Overhead
      Managing thousands of tasks in a standard pool would create massive overhead.
     ForkJoinPool uses a small number of "worker" threads (usually equal to the number of available CPU cores) to handle a massive number of small tasks, keeping the footprint light.

When to Avoid It:
  Avoid for Blocking I/O: If your tasks spend a lot of time waiting for a database or a network API, ForkJoinPool is a poor choice.
                          Since the number of threads is limited to CPU cores, one slow API call can block an entire core. 
                          For I/O-heavy work, a standard ThreadPoolExecutor with a larger thread count is better.

  Don't Overuse the Common Pool: Since ParallelStreams and CompletableFuture share the same global pool, a single heavy task can slow down every other part of your application. 
                                In high-load microservices, it's often better to create your own dedicated ForkJoinPool for specific heavy computations.
